column18: < Ful arsuku 'weath, luck, good fortune' < Ar arzāq 'wealth, good fortune'
-ge does not harmonize to the root (i.e. may be a clitic)  "the plural suffix is added just once, after the first adjective" (Heath 2017, pg. 82)
-yà is the productive plural suffix. Note that the -g in both the singular and plural is a frozen class marker (see Heath 2016, p. 56-57)
final vowel may be fronting due to [j], for example: bě:g (< /bè:gú/) bè:gí yà: ‘stick’
The plural marking is entirely optional in DonnoSo. -mbè is an explicit plural marking for all non-human nouns.

Heath claims that Nonhuman nouns have no special morphology unless they are compounds. Is the gɛ́ of sɛ̀-gɛ́ part of an old noun class marking ? we tend to think so. In Jamsay, plurals can be marked with at the NP level with -bé to emphasize plurality.

column18: The final -ma may be an affix; la racin ga semble apparenté au Gur, ex.  Kóāma gali 'chat'

bè (bê:) means 'child'  The final is L-toned even after an /L/-melody initial. Several combinations (e.g. ‘heart’, ‘tongue’) are highly lexicalized. Semantically transparent ones like ná:-bè ‘calf’ (“cow-child”) are sometimes treated as productive compounds of bé (hence plural -bé:-gè instead of -bè-gè). A nasal linker (-m-bè) is found in at least one case; arguably it is really a prenasalized form of -bè

gù here is a vestigial noun-class suffix; The original suffixal vowel usually harmonizes with a preceding +ATR vowel, but -gu is the default.   Not certain if we want to parse both -ge as I have done here.

suppletive form of child (McPherson 2013, p. 155) ; small is probably parsable cf. child

ɔ̀líí is an adjective meaning 'newborn' or 'young and small' (McPherson 2013, p. 161) writes "ɔ̀lì-ý is an adjective meaning ‘newborn’ or ‘young and small’, but here it is functioning as the possessor of ‘cow’; rather than a usual adjectival construction *nàà ɔ̀lì-ý, we get ɔ̀lì-ý nààL. It is probable that ɔ̀lì-ý in this case is a headless N+Adj phrase. In no other instance have I found ɔ̀lì-ý acting nominally or an adjective acting as a possessor." column18: This form is interesting, because child alone is singular  ì-rⁿú, plural  ì-mú; however here a further deminutive has been made of child, 'little child', singular  ì-rⁿ-í:, plural ì-m-í:. I've reconstructed the plural using the diminutive of child in the plural.

verify tones  Definite markers, especially animate plural wò, may alternatively cliticize to the last occurrence of animate plural suffix -mù in the preceding NP. This may involve jumping over a numeral; see §6.5.3.

Diminutive -ý is undoubtedly related to î: ‘child’. There are also several compounds ending in -î: , which is much more transparently a nominal compound final than the suffix-like -ý. Again the compound initial is tone-dropped. In a few cases both -ý and -î: are attested as variants. For animates (98a-b) the plural replaces î: by úrⁿù-m ‘children’.

Heath, p.48 "Within compounds, there is no spreading of nasalization from the initial to the final. Thus na$Na$-ya&˘ ‘cow’ (“bovine-female”) has unnasalized y. It likewise fails to apply across word-boundaries, even within tightly-knit phrases such as [noun + adjective], e.g. na$Na$ wa$l-gu@ ‘lazy cow’"  nàŋà ná: bé 'cow woman plural'  In these nàŋà forms, is the -ŋá a lexicalised morpheme ? ga, ge, etc ?

column18: What is the wò bit ? Is it -mu ? is it something else ?\\female cow'

Nanga has no singular/plural distinction, nor a human/nonhuman or animate/inanimate distinction, within nominal or (modifying) adjectival morphology. Nanga determiners distinguish animate singular, animate plural, inanimate singular, and inanimate plural, and are therefore the primary vehicle for expressing these categories.  Heath p. 50  In these cases, except ‘woman’, animate singular -ŋ is paired with plural (usually but not always animate) suffix -yè. \\female cow  The word for woman/female seems to be unspecified for number: "as an unmodified simple noun (e.g. indefinite), the singular is yǎ-ŋ, as in yǎ-ŋ gǒ-ɛ̀rɛ̀-Æ ‘a woman went out’. This is the only regular noun stem that preserves animate singular -ŋ"  The female marker that Jeff has here is not used in his grammar where nàŋà alone expresses 'cow'.

(Ivanov, p. 155)? Note Boore (Gur) sṵ̄ɓáró 'donkey'

Here the final -ŋ is surprising in the singular since -nV is the singular human marker and -ŋ the plural human marker-perhaps then there is also a nasal in the root. Thus we reconstruct it as underlying with the -∅ affix of the non human nouns
Here the final -m is surprising since it ressembles the -m suffix of the human plural. Thus we reconstruct -m the underlying nasal with the -∅ affix of the non human noun.

column18: -m is the human plural so what is the m here, root or affix? So far we do not fin -m in a consistant way on animal nouns. Miehe p. 16 claims there was a -wa/-ba singular animal class marker across Gur.

This word and its variants demonstrate a synchronic pattern of nasal stop reduction and apocope. The gú here is probably the suffix of derived nominals seen in Jamsay, but whatever its role, this seems to be lexicalised today (Heath p. 78) variant 2 shows the base. Heath's grammar leaves no clear case. Thus unclear how to build plural; presumably by =mǎ.
Either lenition of the -gu form or a verbal noun in  -ú (Heath p. 78)

column18: What is this jàn ? It does not reappear in the rest of our lexicon. Note Bangime yana 'take'; Peul bandiyanke 'nomad', Peul bayana 'distance'. We find jan in Toro-So jijan 'spider', Proto-Central-Gur *jan 'take' ; there is no clear etymology. ***AH (in prep) zem 'stallion' Arabic dudu???

column18: POV *kpí- Unless ki is an identifiable affix, this seems like a seperate noud. Is ki a preposition for after, so 'after body' = soul ? is the ki of kinde the same as the ki here ? Is this a partial reduplication ? McPherson provides the response, p. 119 "often H-toned CV reduplicants such as kí~kíndé ‘soul’ do not have a full stem equivalent. It could be that these are no longer segmented as reduplicants and so they do not need to take the usual reduplicant L tone. However, segmental cues still exist, such as the word-internal voiceless stop /k/, that indicate that the word must be (or have been) morphologically complex. For more on phonotactics, see section 3.4."

column18: McPherson p. 103 "With certain stems, we see an alternation wherein the unsuffixed stem has a LH tone pattern with H on the final syllable, while the suffixed stem carries all L with H on the suffix. This, I argue, is the result of an underlying rising tone on a light syllable. When there is a following underspecified syllable, this tone crowding can be resolved by shifting the H tone onto that syllable", cf. related stem àbìyɛ\\orphanhood + person

column18: This noun seems proper to Dogon with the final nasal varying and some languages making use of reduplication. Miehe p. 15 reconstructs *ma for Niger-Congo liquids and *-mU for mass nouns. A link to Voltaic is possible if one comapares Nõotre wèndé , Buli wén, Yom ŋmīndə, Nawdm múúnú all meaning 'sun' and which Eddyshaw reconstructs with a Proto Oti-Volta *w "In many languages *w > *ŋ͡m before nasal vowels. Sporadic *wũ > mu/ŋu is quite common" (p.18). .
These forms seem to have lost the initial vowel or CV unit

column18: The first part is difficult to segment. yi- or í and cf. Tommo So jɛ́-ŋɛ́ 'great grandchild', Bangime yáámbɛ̀ 'child', Dagaare (Gur) jángbɪ́ɛ́ 'small child, Pular (Atlantic) jurriya, Mani (Mel) yànt which is very close to the Bondu So form, also Zarma (Songhai) izé, Kaado (SOnghai) zànkà, Note the forms in z- which may correspong to y-elsewhere. Also cf. Bozo juoⁿ, Proto-Bantu jánà.
-nd- commes up across the language (see Hantgan), though its meaning is not immediately transparent, and we may prefer to leave this unsegmented.

Note that the root TEG - TEK comes up elsewhere in Niger-Congo meaning small; Dagaare (Gur) tɪ́kʊ́nɪ́ɪ́, Mani (Mel) ték 'small', Proto-Bantu téeko 'small heap',etc. Hence we have not further parsed this.
